  "topology_notes": [
    "frontend-proxy is the single public entry point. A fault here can affect storefront, Grafana, Jaeger, loadgen, browser OTLP, and flag UI routes.",
    "checkout is the revenue-critical coordinator. Its synchronous blast radius includes cart, valkey-cart, product-catalog, postgresql, currency, shipping, quote, and payment.",
    "email is post-order supporting: checkout logs a warning if order confirmation email fails, but checkout can still return success.",
    "kafka is the async order layer. Degradation affects accounting and fraud-detection, but should not be treated the same as a synchronous checkout failure unless producer errors affect checkout.",
    "postgresql is shared by product-catalog, product-reviews, and accounting. DB pressure can propagate into browse/search, AI reviews, and checkout pricing.",
    "valkey-cart is cart state. Cart or valkey failure directly impacts cart success and checkout preparation.",
    "product-reviews and llm are the main AI product surface. AIOps observes latency/errors and reports correctness as AIE-owned or N/A, not inferred from response time.",
    "flagd and flagd-ui are protected incident-control paths. AIOps may map symptoms and runbooks but must not mutate flags, OpenFeature hooks, or BTC incident delivery.",
    "otel-collector fans out traces to jaeger, metrics to prometheus, and logs to opensearch. Missing or stale telemetry is an incident state, never healthy.",
    "grafana must keep a direct hard-SLO route to tf2-oncall-channel so official alerts still fire if aiops-runtime is down.",
    "aiops-runtime is planned. Default mode should be dry-run with read-only Kubernetes access, SQLite/PVC audit state, and bounded Prometheus/Jaeger/OpenSearch queries.",
    "Do not mark any component as a confirmed SPOF from this static JSON alone. Validate deployed replicas, state durability, and failover behavior in EKS."
  ]
